  "body": "## üéâ Description\r\n\r\nOverflow tests are using integers which are way above Javascript's MAX_SAFE_INTEGER.\r\n\r\n- [x] üêõ This is a bug report.\r\n- [ ] üìà This is a feature request.\r\n\r\n## üíª Environment\r\n\r\nAny platform.\r\n\r\n## üìù Details\r\n\r\nIn the overflow tests for SafeMath.sol, you are using integers which are way above Javascript's MAX_SAFE_INTEGER. Whether or not these tests work, I think is by mere coincidence (kind of *undefined behavior*, if this terminology applies for Javascript).\r\n\r\n## üî¢ Code To Reproduce Issue\r\n\r\n```\r\nlet x = 115792089237316195423570985008687907853269984665640564039457584007913129639935;\r\nlet y = 115792089237316195423570985008687907853269984665640564039457584007913129639936;\r\nalert(x < y);\r\n```\r\n\r\nUPDATE:\r\n\r\nIn fact, this test passes by cheating.\r\n\r\nIt checks for `revert`, where the actual error to be expected is `invalid opcode`.\r\nThis is because the `SafeMath.sol` contract uses `assert`s rather than `require`s.\r\n\r\nSo the fix should include:\r\n\r\n1. Replace each one of those large integers with `web3.toBigNumber(\"...\")`.\r\n2. Replace each `assertRevert` with `assertJump`.\r\n\r\nAlternatively for the 1st bullet (a more appropriate fix IMO), you can simply use:\r\n\r\n    let a = web3.toBigNumber(2).pow(256).minus(1)\r\n\r\nBTW, I haven't been quite able to determine why a `revert` exception is thrown here to begin with.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nHere is the exact fix that I have used:\r\n\r\n```\r\n  it('should throw an error on addition overflow', async function () {\r\n    let a = web3.toBigNumber(2).pow(256).minus(1);\r\n    let b = 1;\r\n    try {\r\n      await safeMath.add(a, b);\r\n      assert.fail('should have thrown before');\r\n    } catch (error) {\r\n      assertJump(error);\r\n    }\r\n  });\r\n\r\n  it('should throw an error on multiplication overflow', async function () {\r\n    let a = web3.toBigNumber(2).pow(256).div(2);\r\n    let b = 2;\r\n    try {\r\n      await safeMath.multiply(a, b);\r\n      assert.fail('should have thrown before');\r\n    } catch (error) {\r\n      assertJump(error);\r\n    }\r\n  });\r\n```\r\n",
